PART 1: JUNIOR LEVEL - Core Concepts

Section 1.1: What is Virtio?

The Problem Before Virtio

Full Device Emulation (pre-2008):

```c
// Guest writes to emulated hardware register
outb(0x3F0, data);  // Floppy controller I/O port

// Host VMM (QEMU) traps the I/O
static void floppy_write(void *opaque, uint32_t addr, uint32_t val)
{
    // 1. VM Exit (expensive ~1000 CPU cycles)
    // 2. Emulate floppy controller state machine
    // 3. Translate to host disk access
    // 4. Return to guest
    // Total: ~5000 CPU cycles per I/O!
}
```

The Result:

· Network throughput: ~100 Mbps (vs 10 Gbps native)
· Disk IOPS: ~10k (vs 1M native)
· CPU overhead: 50%+ for I/O-intensive workloads

The Virtio Solution

Paravirtualization with shared memory:

```c
// Guest driver (Linux kernel)
static void virtio_net_xmit(struct sk_buff *skb)
{
    // 1. Map socket buffer to DMA addresses
    // 2. Fill descriptor table (1-2 CPU cycles)
    // 3. Add to available ring (1 CPU cycle)
    // 4. Write doorbell (VM Exit ~1000 cycles)
    // Total: ~1002 CPU cycles per I/O
    // 5x improvement vs full emulation!
}
```

Key Insight: Virtio is a communication protocol, not an emulation of hardware.

