Section 2.3: Memory Management Deep Dive

GPA → HVA Translation Pipeline

```c
// QEMU's address space translation
static void *virtqueue_map_desc(VirtQueue *vq, 
                                struct iovec *iov,
                                unsigned int *num,
                                uint64_t addr, 
                                uint32_t len,
                                bool is_write)
{
    // 1. Get MemoryRegion for this GPA
    MemoryRegionSection *section = address_space_find(
        vq->vdev->dma_as, 
        addr, 
        len, 
        is_write ? &addr : NULL
    );
    
    // 2. Translate to HVA
    if (memory_region_is_ram(section->mr)) {
        // Direct mapping: GPA → HVA
        void *hva = memory_region_get_ram_ptr(section->mr);
        hva += section->offset_within_region;
        return hva + (addr - section->offset_within_address_space);
    } else {
        // Non-RAM: Need bounce buffer
        // Allocate temporary buffer, copy data
        void *bounce = g_malloc(len);
        if (is_write) {
            // For reads: copy to bounce buffer first
            address_space_read(as, addr, bounce, len);
        }
        return bounce;
    }
}
```

Performance Implications:

Operation Cost
MemoryRegion lookup ~100 ns
GPA → HVA translation ~50 ns
Bounce buffer allocation ~500 ns
Data copy (4KB) ~100 ns

Optimization Strategies:

1. Use RAM-only regions: Avoid bounce buffers
2. Batch translations: Map multiple pages at once
3. Use huge pages: 2MB pages reduce TLB misses

