Section 3.1: Feature Negotiation Deep Dive

The Feature Negotiation Protocol

```
GUEST DRIVER                          QEMU DEVICE
    │                                      │
    │ 1. Read device_features              │
    │    (what device supports)            │
    │ ◄─────────────────────────────────────│
    │                                      │
    │ 2. Calculate driver_features         │
    │    (what driver supports)            │
    │    = device_features & driver_supports│
    │                                      │
    │ 3. Write driver_features             │
    │ ─────────────────────────────────────►│
    │                                      │
    │ 4. Device validates                  │
    │    = driver_features & device_features│
    │                                      │
    │ 5. Write VIRTIO_PCI_STATUS_DRIVER_OK │
    │ ─────────────────────────────────────►│
    │                                      │
    │ 6. Device enables negotiated features│
    └──────────────────────────────────────┘
```

Feature Flags Deep Dive

VIRTIO_F_VERSION_1 (bit 32) - Virtio 1.0

· Mandatory for all modern drivers
· Enables 64-bit addresses and modern PCI
· If not set, device is legacy (0.9.5)
· Principal insight: Legacy mode is 30% slower

VIRTIO_F_RING_PACKED (bit 34) - Packed Virtqueue

· Single ring replaces split (descriptor/avail/used)
· Better cache locality (all data in one memory region)
· Performance improvement: 10-15% for small I/O
· NVIDIA interest: GPUs work better with packed queues

VIRTIO_F_IN_ORDER (bit 35) - In-Order Descriptors

· Device processes descriptors in driver order
· No need for used ring IDs (simpler)
· Trade-off: Less parallelization (queue depth limited)

VIRTIO_F_IOMMU_PLATFORM (bit 33) - IOMMU Support

· Guest manages DMA addresses via IOMMU
· Security: Prevents DMA attacks between VMs
· AMD SEV: Required for encrypted VMs

VIRTIO_F_ACCESS_PLATFORM (bit 36) - Access Platform

· Device access to guest memory is mediated
· Qualcomm interest: ARM SMMU integration

Feature Negotiation Example (Principal Level)

```c
static uint64_t echo_get_features(VirtIODevice *vdev, 
                                  uint64_t features, 
                                  Error **errp)
{
    // 1. Mandatory features (always on)
    features |= (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_VERSION_1);
    features |= (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_RING_PACKED);
    
    // 2. Optional features (negotiable)
    if (echo->supports_in_order) {
        features |= (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_IN_ORDER);
    }
    
    // 3. Security features (must be enabled for confidential VMs)
    if (vdev->use_iommu) {
        features |= (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_IOMMU_PLATFORM);
        features |= (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_ACCESS_PLATFORM);
    }
    
    return features;
}

static void echo_device_realize(DeviceState *dev, Error **errp)
{
    // ... (previous code)
    
    // Check for security requirements
    if (is_confidential_vm()) {
        if (!(dev->features & (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_IOMMU_PLATFORM))) {
            error_setg(errp, "Confidential VM requires IOMMU");
            return;
        }
    }
    
    // Allocate virtqueues based on negotiated features
    if (dev->features & (1ULL << VIRTIO_F_RING_PACKED)) {
        echo->vq = virtio_add_queue_packed(vdev, 256, echo_handle_output);
    } else {
        echo->vq = virtio_add_queue(vdev, 256, echo_handle_output);
    }
}
```

