Staff Question: You need to choose between vhost-net and vhost-user for a 5G telecom application requiring 100Gbps throughput with <10μs latency. Which do you choose?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Choice: vhost-user with DPDK

Reasoning:

1. Throughput: 100Gbps requires DPDK poll-mode drivers. Kernel cannot sustain this due to interrupt overhead.
2. Latency: DPDK bypasses kernel, avoiding:
   · Interrupt handling (~1-2μs)
   · Kernel scheduling (~5-10μs)
   · System call overhead (~100ns)
3. vhost-net limitations:
   · Kernel networking stack adds overhead (TCP/IP processing)
   · Interrupt-based or NAPI (not poll-mode)
   · Maximum ~40Gbps on high-end hardware
4. vhost-user advantages:
   · Userspace control of NIC (DPDK PMD)
   · Batch packet processing (64 packets per burst)
   · Zero-copy between guest and NIC
   · CPU affinity (pin to specific cores)
5. Trade-offs:
   · More complex (DPDK learning curve)
   · CPU overhead (100% core usage for polling)
   · But acceptable for dedicated 5G workload

