Q11: What is the performance impact of VM exits in virtio?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Each VM exit costs ~1000-2000 CPU cycles on x86 (or ~500-1000ns).

Impact on I/O:

· Each I/O requires at least 1 VM exit (doorbell)
· Plus 1 VM entry (interrupt)
· Total ~2000-4000 cycles per I/O
· For 1M IOPS, that's 2-4 billion cycles (too high!)

Optimization:

· Polling mode: Guest busy-waits used ring (no VM exits)
· Batching: Process multiple descriptors per VM exit
· Event index: Interrupt only when needed

</details>

Q12: What is packed virtqueue and why is it better?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Packed virtqueue (virtio 1.1+) uses a single ring instead of split rings (descriptor + avail + used).

Benefits:

1. Better cache locality: All data in one memory region
2. Fewer cache misses: One memory region vs three
3. Simpler driver: No separate rings to manage
4. Smaller footprint: ~8KB vs ~16KB (for 256 descriptors)

Performance: 10-15% improvement for small I/O workloads.

</details>

Q13: How does interrupt coalescing work?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Interrupt coalescing reduces interrupt rate by batching notifications:

```c
// Device waits for:
// 1. At least N descriptors processed, OR
// 2. At least T microseconds elapsed
// Then sends one interrupt for all N descriptors

coalesce_params = {
    .batch_size = 64,      // Interrupt after 64 descriptors
    .timeout_ns = 100000,  // Or after 100μs
};
```

Effect: Reduces interrupts from 100k/sec to ~10k/sec, lowering CPU overhead.

</details>

Q14: What is the event index?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Event index is a more advanced interrupt suppression mechanism (VIRTIO_RING_F_EVENT_IDX).

How it works:

· Driver tells device: "Interrupt me when used ring reaches index X"
· Device interrupts only when used->idx >= event_idx
· Driver updates event_idx after processing interrupts

Compared to flags:

· Flags: "Interrupt me" or "Don't interrupt me" (coarse)
· Event index: "Interrupt me at this exact point" (fine-grained)

Result: Fewer interrupts and lower latency.

</details>

